Capital punishment is legal in most countries of the [[Middle East]]. Much of the motivation for the retention of the death penalty has been religious in nature, as [[Islam and capital punishment|the Qur'an allows or mandates executions]] for various offences.
==Moratoria and abolition== ===Israel=== Almost all death penalties were abolished by legislation in 1954 except for serious crimes committed during wartime. The last execution to ever take place in Israel was that of [[Adolf Eichmann]], who was convicted for his role in the Holocaust, in 1962. A moratorium has since been placed on all further execution.
In 2018 January 2018, [[Knesset]] passed a bill introducing death penalty for [[terrorism]].<ref name="DeathPenaltyHalamish">{{cite news|title=Netanyahu demands death penalty for Halamish terrorist|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-demands-death-penalty-for-halamish-terrorist/|accessdate=27 July 2017|publisher=Times of Israel|date=27 July 2017}}</ref><ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-5188931/Israeli-leaders-push-terrorist-death-penalty.html</ref><ref>http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/israel-will-todesstrafe-fuer-terroristen-einfuehren-15347505.html</ref><ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-palestinians-deathpenalty/israeli-death-penalty-advocates-win-preliminary-vote-in-parliament-idUSKBN1ES1DT</ref>
===Turkey=== In Turkey, capital punishment was fully abolished in 2004 for all crimes. {{citation needed|date=September 2011}}
==Abolition advocacy== ===Attempts=== In Lebanon in 2008, then-Justice Minister [[Ibrahim Najjar]] introduced a draft law to Parliament which would abolish the death penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Politics/Oct/11/Najjar-presents-draft-law-to-abolish-death-penalty.ashx|title = Najjar presents draft law to abolish death penalty|publisher = The Daily Star|date = October 11, 2008<!-- 12:00 AM-->}}</ref> While the law failed to pass, he continued to advocate for the abolition for the rest of his time in office.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Politics/Aug/29/Justice-Ministry-campaigns-to-abolish-death-penalty.ashx|title = Justice Ministry campaigns to abolish death penalty|author = Josie Ensor|publisher = The Daily Star|date = August 29, 2009<!-- 12:00 AM-->}}</ref>
Farouk Ksentini, chairman of Algeria's National Advisory Commission for the Protection and Promotion of Human Rights (CNCPPDH), stated in 2010 that he would advocate for the abolition of the death penalty. This aroused opposition from Islamist groups.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/en_GB/features/awi/features/2010/03/11/feature-02|title = Algeria resurrects death penalty debate|author = Ademe Amine|publisher = Maghrebia|date = 2010-03-11}}</ref>
