{{short description|12th-century illegitimate son of King Henry I of England}} '''Henry FitzRoy''' (born c. 1100-1104, died 1158) was an illegitimate son of [[Henry I of England]] by [[Nest ferch Rhys|Nest]], daughter of [[Rhys ap Tewdwr]], last king of Deheubarth (d. 1093), and his wife, Gwladys ferch Rhiwallon ap Cynfyn.<ref>Roger Turvey, ''The Welsh Princes 1063-1283</ref>
Henry FitzRoy held lands from his royal father in [[Narberth, Pembrokeshire|Narberth]] and Pebidiog. Upon his death in battle against the Welsh Prince in 1158, his lands passed to his oldest son, [[Meiler FitzHenry|Meilyr]], later [[Lord Chief Justice of Ireland]] for his cousin, [[Henry II of England|King Henry II]]. Amabilis, daughter of Henry FitzRoy, married [[Walter de Riddlesford]]. Her husband Walter, along with Amabilis's uncles, her nephews and the Geralds were active in Irish affairs as well as holding large grants of land there.<ref>"An Hitherto Unnoted Descent from King Henry I", ''NEHGR'', Vol. 116, Oct. 1962, p. 278-279</ref>
In 1158 Henry FitzRoy led a naval expedition in an attempt to 'assault' the Welsh under [[Owain Gwynedd]], [[List of rulers of Gwynedd|King of Gwynedd]] 'on both land and sea', on behalf of his Norman cousin, King [[Henry II of England|Henry II]].<ref>[http://meysyddbrwydro.cbhc.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Coleshill-1157-Border-Archaeology-2009.pdf ''Welsh Battlefields, Historical Research: Coleshill (1157)'']; Border Archaeology.</ref> When FitzRoy's army landed at [[Anglesey|Ynys Môn]], he torched the churches of [[Llanbedrgoch]] and [[Llanfair Mathafarn Eithaf]]. During Owain's men gathered together and the next morning fought and defeated the Norman army and killed Henry FitzRoy by a "shower of lances".
